Given a Bernoulli distribution for the probability of snow presence:

$$y_i \sim Bernoulli(\theta_i)$$

And a Beta distribution for modeling theta:

$$\theta_i \sim Beta(\alpha, \beta)$$

The combination of these two distributions (as a joint distribution) for Bayes rule looks like:

$$p(\theta|y) = \theta^{\sum y_i} (1 - \theta)^{n - \sum y_i} \dfrac{\Gamma(\alpha + \beta)}{\Gamma(\alpha) \Gamma(\beta)}\theta^{\alpha - 1} (1 - \theta)^{\beta - 1}$$

We can combine like terms to get a distribution that looks like:

$$p(\theta|y) = \dfrac{\Gamma(\alpha + \beta)}{\Gamma(\alpha) \Gamma(\beta)} \theta^{\sum y_i + \alpha - 1} (1 - \theta)^{n + \beta - 1 - \sum y_i} $$

This resembles the kernel for a Beta distribution!  Which means

$$p(\theta | y) \propto Beta(\sum y_i + \alpha - 1, n + \beta - \sum y_i - 1)$$
